    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-30T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-30T22:00:00-05:00" n="931"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d931">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/6–3044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-30T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 30, 1944—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1602. Embassy’s 2327 June 28, midnight. As you will have seen from the
                    Department’s 5111 [<hi rend="italic">1581</hi>], June 28, 9 p.m.,<note n="57"
                        xml:id="d931fn57">See footnote 50, <ref target="#pg_863">p.
                        863</ref>.</note> our Embassy at Ankara has been authorized to support
                    British efforts to persuade the Turks to sever economic and diplomatic relations
                    with the Axis. This step does not preclude pressure on the Turks to go further
                    along the lines of Molotov’s proposal to the Turks to enter the war, if it is
                    agreed that this course is militarily desirable in the light of present
                    circumstances. A statement of the current Russian view on this point is awaited
                    with interest.</p>
                <p>Steinhardt is expected in Washington about July 3 and will be consulted on the
                    practical aspects of obtaining from Turkey at this time the cooperation which
                    will contribute most effectively to the Allied cause.</p>
                <p>Repeated to London and to Ankara</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
